-To prevent subsequent torsion, fix the contralateral testis to the scrotal wall with 3-4 non absorbable sutures. (Orchidopexy). This is also important because bilateral involvement --ie, the "bell clapper" deformity (lack of fixation of the cord structures by the testicular mediastinum) --and the high incidence of recurrent torsion and infertility in bilateral cases.

\section*{Complications}
1. Delay of more than $4-6$ hours between onset of symptoms and the time of surgical (or manual) detorsion reduces the salvage rate to $55-85 \%$.
2. Retention of an injured testis can induce pathologic changes to the contralateral testis.
3.Recurence if orchidopexy not done
